@node "Cnet" "Filepather in Cnet"

 How to utilize Filepather (FP) in CNET - by Neurodancer/ABYSS.
 ==============================================================

 Okey  dudes, this won't  be  very  difficult,  as  CNet  is a highly
 developed BBS program. :) ...unless some other bearing cryptic chars in 
 their names, adding coolness to it...  :)

 1. Textfiles (suffixes .txt, .dok, .doc, .nfo)
 ----------------------------------------------
 Since textfiles usually can't be tested for their integrity, and since
 with the use of FP you don't need no Aqua-Fuck-Fast-kill-me-now-adder
 for your textfiles, I strongly recommend you to include FP as checker
 for  those filetypes, instead of adding more crap to a solid textfile,
 making it close-to-unreadable.

 Start  the  CNET  configprogram,  enter the Archivers section, if they don't
 exist  already create entries for the above filetypes and enter at the "Test
 format" stringbox:  "filepather >%s FILE %s".

 Leave all other boxes free, you can of course add as "Pack format" the usual
 "<do  not  remove  .TXT>"  which  CNet  has  set by default for textfiles.

 2. Archives (suffixes .lha, .lzh, .zip)
 ---------------------------------------
 As  you  might  guess,  we  are  using the xscripts for the purpose of
 filepathering an archive.  If you already have xscripts (for stripping etc.)
 simply  add  this  line  to  your  "xlha2lha",  "xlzh2lzh"  and "xzip2zip"
 xscripts located in your S:  directory to be active (and to the others FP
 might support in the future!):

 a) without output given to the BBS screen:

  Filepather >nil: FILE "{PATHF}"

 b) with the FP output displayed in the BBS:

  delete >nil: t:result.txt FORCE
  Filepather >t:result.txt FILE "{PATHF}"

 additionally, load your "bbstext" in your fav editor, and paste in at line
 1909 (CNet/3), before it says
        "\n1Transformation completed.\n1"

   "\n1{*0 t:result.txt}

   (Obviously, "\" is a Ctrl-Y and "{" is a Ctrl-Q MCI introducer)
   You surely noticed this is a very cheap trick. But it works, so
   what?

 Thats all there is to do! Now go and use it, and throw away all your BBS adds
 that only get on everyones nerves! :)

 Neurodancer/ABYSS.
@endnode

@node "Tempest" "Filepather in Tempest"

 How to use Filepather with TEMPEST BBS:
 =======================================

 Simply change your add-scripts (add_lha; add_zip; add_(txt|nfo|...) to the
 following (as you won't need any more bbs-adds):

 Filepather FILE %s

 Thats all! Output will be redirected to the Tempest BBS screen automatically.

 Typed by Anti-g (Sysop/Outer Space).
@endnode

@node "Xenolink" "Filepather for Xenolink"

 .KEY FileName
 .BRA <
 .KET >

 ; Xenolink script file for archive testing
 ; This script file tests files ending in .LHA

 FAILAT 1

 ; Add FilePather line

 Xenolink:Utilities/FilePather >NIL: File "<FileName>"

 ; Test archive

 LHA >NIL: -q t "<FileName>"
@endnode

@node "Excelsior" "Filepather for Excelsior! BBS"

 How to use Filepather with Excelsior! BBS:
 ==========================================

 1. Archives:

     Start XPrefs (RAmiga+p when the 'Master Server' window is activated),
     and press the "Archive" button. Then you click on the different
     extensions in the "Archives" list, and change the "Add Text"
     information to:

          "Filepather File %s"

     for those archives that you wish to have processed by Filepather.

 2. Text files:

     If you want your text-files to be checked by FilePather as well,
     enter the "Archive" window in XPrefs, then you choose "Add", and
     enter 'TXT', 'DOC', or whatever you wish, as "Archive Name".
     Then you enter:

          "Filepather File %s"

     in the "Add Text" stringbox, and leave the other boxes empty.

 Description by:
  Magnus Johnson, Sysop at Cyber Zonen and Filepather beta tester.
@endnode

@node "Reccoon" "Filepather for Reccoon"

 How to use Filepather with Reccoon:
 ===================================

 Just add a "int FileCopy(string);" (without quotes) before the 'return;'
 in RcnHooks.FPL and then, at the end of the file, insert this:

 --- 8< ---
   int FileCopy(string fil)
   {
      string buf;

      buf = CookString("c:FilePather <Temp Uploads>/Tmp~sl%d~/");
      SimpleDOS(buf);
      return(0);
   }
 --- 8< ---

 NOTE! <Temp Uploads> must be the path of where the files are stored
 during a batch upload (see config prg, system paths).

 Written by Henric Andersson, sysop Elsewhere Development.
@endnode

@node "Max" "Filepather for MAXsBBS"

 How to use Filepather with MAXsBBS:
 ===================================

 FPD is a door by Anders Gustafsson to MAXsBBS (Anthony Barrett), which
 makes it possible to use FilePather on new files.

 It's VERY easy to install! Read the separate instructions for more details.

@endnode

@node "DLG" "Filepather for DLG"

 How to use Filepather with DLG:
 ===============================

 Setting up FilePather to work with DLG is very simple:

 Go to dlgconfig:batch. There you may (or may not) have a file called
 upload1.batch. This is the script that is run when someone has just
 completed an upload and is just about to enter a description.
 If you don't have this batchfile it's nothing to worry about.
 Just create it. My upload1.batch looks like this:

 .key username/a,filename/a
 .bra "["
 .ket "]"
 c:FilePather [filename]

 This version will display a couple of lines on the users screen telling
 him that Filepather is being run. If you don't want this, ie. you don't
 want to inform the user that Filepather is running then just change the
 last line to:

 c:Filepather >nil: [filename]

 And that's it :-)
@endnode

